    <a href="/reading/the-natural-framework-lean/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to lean navigator</a>

    <h1>Pigeonhole.lean</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6"><a href="https://github.com/kimjune01/natural-framework/blob/master/NaturalFramework/Pigeonhole.lean"><img src="/reading/github.svg" alt="gh" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>View source on GitHub</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Proves the pigeonhole principle from scratch: you cannot injectively map n+1 items into n slots, so at least two must collide.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>compress</h3>
    <p>A helper that removes one element from <code>Fin (n+1)</code>, compressing the remaining elements into <code>Fin n</code>. Elements below the removed value keep their index; elements above shift down by 1.</p>
    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-blue-300"><code><span class="text-blue-300">private def</span> <span class="text-green-300">compress</span> &#123;n : Nat&#125; (v x : Fin (n + 1)) (h : x &ne; v) : Fin n :=
  <span class="text-blue-300">if</span> hlt : x.val &lt; v.val <span class="text-blue-300">then</span>
    &langle;x.val, <span class="text-blue-300">by</span> omega&rangle;
  <span class="text-blue-300">else</span>
    &langle;x.val - 1, <span class="text-blue-300">by</span> ...&rangle;</code></pre>

    <h3>Fin.no_injection</h3>
    <p>There is no injective function from <code>Fin (n+1)</code> to <code>Fin n</code>. Proved by induction on n with element removal at each step.</p>
    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-blue-300"><code><span class="text-blue-300">theorem</span> <span class="text-green-300">Fin.no_injection</span> (n : Nat)
    : &forall; g : Fin (n + 1) &rarr; Fin n, &not; Function.Injective g</code></pre>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">Base case: <code>Fin 1 &rarr; Fin 0</code> is impossible since <code>Fin 0</code> is empty. Inductive step: given <code>g : Fin (k+2) &rarr; Fin (k+1)</code>, remove the image of the last element from the codomain. The compressed function <code>g' : Fin (k+1) &rarr; Fin k</code> inherits injectivity, contradicting the induction hypothesis.</p>

    <h3>pigeonhole</h3>
    <p>Among N+1 values in <code>Fin N</code>, at least two must collide. The collision gives specific indices i &lt; j where <code>f i = f j</code>.</p>
    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-blue-300"><code><span class="text-blue-300">theorem</span> <span class="text-green-300">pigeonhole</span> &#123;N : Nat&#125; (f : Fin (N + 1) &rarr; Fin N)
    : &exists; i j : Fin (N + 1), i &lt; j &and; f i = f j</code></pre>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">Uses <code>Fin.no_injection</code> by contradiction: if no collision existed, f would be injective, which is impossible.</p>

    <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Pigeonhole: N+1 items into N slots => collision
# This is why bounded transducers must repeat states.

def find_collision(values, num_slots):
    """Map N+1 values into Fin(N). Return colliding pair."""
    seen = {}
    for i, v in enumerate(values):
        slot = v % num_slots
        if slot in seen:
            return (seen[slot], i, slot)
        seen[slot] = i
    return None  # impossible if len(values) > num_slots

N = 4
items = list(range(N + 1))  # 5 items into 4 slots
i, j, slot = find_collision(items, N)
print(f"{N+1} items into {N} slots:")
print(f"  item[{i}]={items[i]} and item[{j}]={items[j]}"
      f" both map to slot {slot}")
print(f"  Collision guaranteed — no injection from"
      f" Fin({N+1}) to Fin({N})")
`} />

    <h3>pigeonhole_nat</h3>
    <p>A convenience wrapper for Nat-indexed sequences: among values f(0), ..., f(N), at least two in <code>Fin N</code> must collide.</p>

